Dear Ananda,

Until now, my favorite commentary on the Gayatri mantra is a Sanskrit
commentary by Painganadu Ganapati Shastry. He had the distinction of being
one of the teachers of the Paramacharyal of Kanchi.

He writes: "You can pray to the devata of your choice with the Gayatri
mantra -- be it Krishna, Rama, Hayagriva, Skanda, Parvati, Lakshmi,
Sarasvati, Indra, Ganesha, Shiva, Vishnu, or any other deity ... as they all
reside in the solar orb ... they all reside in the the orb of Savita. What
is important is to have patience and develop a deep focus of mind. With
practice, slowly, even the impossible becomes possible." He then gives four
different "practical" explanations of the gayatri mantra, with the deity as
(a) savita, (b) narayana, (c) parama-shiva and (d) paramatma.

> Gayatri Devi, the Goddess of Gayatri is the Deity


Traditionally, we invoke her with the "aayaatu varadaa ..." and "ojo.si ..."
mantras. What is striking is how hard the mantras try not to limit Her while
attempting to describe Her.

sasneham,

   ajit




